    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-01-10T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-01-10T18:00:00-05:00" n="95"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d95">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/3422: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fish</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-11T01:00:00+02:00"
                            >January 11, 1936—1 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2. Important reinforcements of British mechanized military units arrived in Egypt
                    this week. I learn from reliable source that by the middle of next month British
                    troops in this country are expected to be considerably in excess of existing
                    strength. Divisional headquarters <pb facs="0153" n="88" xml:id="pg_88"/> for
                    the forces stationed the western desert have been established at Alexandria
                    under the command of Major General Howard, recently arrived. Reenforcement and
                    strengthening of the principal British base in the western desert at Mersa
                    Matruh is proceeding apace.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Fish</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
